Question: Having a look at the implementation of processHooks, I realized we should unify the usage, especially in the context of the error case. Sometimes we are catching the error and creating a UserNotification:
 return processHooks(
      ...
 ).catch(
     error => UserNotification.error(`Executing search failed with error: ${error}`, 'Could not execute search'),
);

sometimes we are using the processHooks onError argument, to set the hookComponent state
return viewLoader(
      ...
      (e) => {
        if (e instanceof Error) {
          throw e;
        }
        this.setState({ hookComponent: e });
      },

and sometimes we are doing the same, but without checking the error instance.
My main question is related to the hookComponent. It looks like we are defining a hookComponent when processHooks errors. When the hookComponent is defined we'll display it instead of the ExtendedSearchPage. I want to test tis case, but looking at the code I don't understand when the hookComponent (e.g. in the last code snippet) gets defined. because when it is an error, setState will not get called. When it is not an error, the onError function passed to processHooks will not getCalled.

